{"id":"1508.04451","submitter":"Satoru Morita","authors":"Satoru Morita","title":"Six Susceptible-Infected-Susceptible Models on Scale-free Networks","comments":"6 pages, 1 figure","journal-ref":"Scientific Reports 6, Article number: 22506 (2016)","doi":"10.1038/srep22506","report-no":null,"categories":"physics.soc-ph cond-mat.stat-mech cs.SI nlin.AO q-bio.PE","license":"http://arxiv.org/licenses/nonexclusive-distrib/1.0/","abstract":"  Spreading phenomena are ubiquitous in nature and society. For example,\ndisease, rumor, and information spread over underlying social and information\nnetworks. It is well known that there is no threshold for epidemic models on\nscale-free networks; this suggests that disease can spread on such networks,\nregardless of how low the contact rate may be. In this paper, I consider six\nmodels with different contact and propagation mechanisms. Each model is\nanalyzed by degree-based mean-field theory. I show that the presence or absence\nof an outbreak threshold depends on the contact and propagation mechanism.\n","versions":[{"version":"v1","created":"Sun, 16 Aug 2015 13:03:18 GMT"}],"update_date":"2016-03-16"}
